00:31:25,549 --> 00:31:30,253
Comrades, comrades, what is
happening here?

456
00:31:30,321 --> 00:31:34,925
Greenberg wants to emigrate to
Israel

457
00:31:34,992 --> 00:31:41,030
and professor Gross can find
nothing better than to accuse
him of treason?!

458
00:31:41,098 --> 00:31:44,801
Of course, we all know that
Greenberg is a traitor.

459
00:31:44,868 --> 00:31:51,841
Our nation fed him, nourished
Greenberg, spent money for his
education,

460
00:31:51,908 --> 00:31:56,012
and now he wants to emigrate to
Israel,

461
00:31:56,080 --> 00:31:59,515
to give his knowledge to our
imperialistic enemies,

462
00:31:59,583 --> 00:32:03,119
to the enemies of the all
progressive humankind!

463
00:32:03,187 --> 00:32:07,990
Comrades, I think we should
petition the authorities not to
allow this!

464
00:32:08,058 --> 00:32:12,395
Greenberg's place is not Israel,
it's prison!

465
00:32:12,463 --> 00:32:19,169
What do you think about that?

466
00:32:19,236 --> 00:32:24,073
You, Tolik Gurov!
You used to be his friend!

467
00:32:24,141 --> 00:32:32,047
Come up here!
Tell us what you think!

468
00:32:32,115 --> 00:32:40,890
This is true. Sasha was my
friend... I am sorry...

469
00:32:40,957 --> 00:32:47,597
Who could have known?
Who could have guessed?

470
00:32:47,665 --> 00:32:55,871
I will try to not have friends
again... I mean, such friends.

471
00:33:11,121 --> 00:33:15,024
This is better, with the water.
In case it's bugged.

472
00:33:15,091 --> 00:33:16,726
You're not mad at me, are you?

473
00:33:16,794 --> 00:33:18,628
He just left me no choice.

474
00:33:18,696 --> 00:33:23,032
It doesn't matter what I say.
You're leaving anyway.

475
00:33:23,100 --> 00:33:25,034
I'm the one who has to stay
here...

476
00:33:25,102 --> 00:33:27,837
Maybe I should leave too?
What do you think?

477
00:33:27,905 --> 00:33:31,107
Just because Galileo publicly
denied his beliefs,

478
00:33:31,175 --> 00:33:34,677
the Earth did not stop orbiting
the Sun.

479
00:33:34,745 --> 00:33:41,351
It is all, like Hamlet said,
words, words, words.

480
00:33:50,261 --> 00:33:51,628
Thanks.

481
00:33:51,695 --> 00:33:53,530
For what?

482
00:33:53,597 --> 00:33:55,665
For being the only one to not
say anything.

483
00:33:55,732 --> 00:33:57,600
Was I?

484
00:33:57,668 --> 00:33:59,502
Yes.

485
00:33:59,570 --> 00:34:03,172
It's alright. It's just a
ritual, anyway. No one really
thinks like that.

486
00:34:03,240 --> 00:34:06,042
Yeah. Right.

487
00:34:06,109 --> 00:34:10,680
Want to come over? I have some
vodka... OK? Let's go.

488
00:34:10,747 --> 00:34:14,350
No shame! No shame at all!

489
00:34:14,418 --> 00:34:23,293
Now they're bringing men to the rooms...
Oh, wait till I call the police.

490
00:34:23,360 --> 00:34:31,534
Don't pay any attention.
She's totally harmless.

491
00:34:31,802 --> 00:34:34,304
You know, I was in love with you
our freshmen year.

492
00:34:34,371 --> 00:34:37,940
I suspected it.
Why didn't you say something?

493
00:34:38,008 --> 00:34:39,375
Everybody was in love with you.

494
00:34:39,443 --> 00:34:44,547
Swarms of Casanovas...
I was too shy.

495
00:34:44,615 --> 00:34:49,152
Shall we drink to your
departure, yeah?

496
00:34:56,493 --> 00:34:59,862
It's a little strange -
everybody wanted to be with you
and you're still not married.

497
00:34:59,930 --> 00:35:06,703
Yeah, I'm too picky.
Why aren't you married?

498
00:35:06,770 --> 00:35:08,571
I guess I'm too picky also.

499
00:35:08,639 --> 00:35:13,609
To the picky ones.

500
00:35:13,677 --> 00:35:19,181
You may stay here, if you want.

501
00:35:23,286 --> 00:35:26,255
It's hard to believe you're
leaving us.

502
00:35:26,323 --> 00:35:33,796
We'll never see each other
again. "Never".

503
00:35:33,864 --> 00:35:37,433
Never-never-never-never

504
00:35:37,501 --> 00:35:41,671
It's a strange word...Never.

505
00:35:41,739 --> 00:35:45,841
It's not definite yet.

506
00:35:45,909 --> 00:35:53,383
I'm the first PhD physicist to
apply for emigration. They may
not let me out.

507
00:35:53,450 --> 00:35:59,689
Oh, you will leave.
And a good thing too.

508
00:35:59,757 --> 00:36:01,724
You'll be happy there...

509
00:36:01,792 --> 00:36:08,264
Just don't try being noble right
now and asking me to marry you
so we could leave together.

510
00:36:08,332 --> 00:36:15,338
My life's already planned out.
I'll never make a good wife, I'm afraid.

511
00:36:15,406 --> 00:36:23,012
I can't serve astrophysics and a
man too at the same time.

512
00:36:23,079 --> 00:36:27,850
I would like to have a baby,
though...

513
00:36:27,918 --> 00:36:34,957
and I think sometimes: what if I
pick one of you guys, one of the
best, and get pregnant.

514
00:36:35,025 --> 00:36:39,028
I would hide it from the father,
of course.

515
00:36:39,095 --> 00:36:44,299
It's easier to care for a child without
having to care for a man too, huh?

516
00:36:44,367 --> 00:36:46,669
So, there is theory in your
solitude.

517
00:36:46,737 --> 00:36:50,439
Well, then, in mine too.

518
00:36:50,507 --> 00:36:54,076
I have thought of leaving many
times,

519
00:36:54,144 --> 00:36:56,779
I just couldn't figure out how.

520
00:36:56,847 --> 00:36:58,948
I've thought of defecting even.

521
00:36:59,016 --> 00:37:01,651
What would I do with a wife?

522
00:37:01,718 --> 00:37:09,125
It's just pure luck for me that
emigration started when it did...

523
00:37:20,203 --> 00:37:28,578
What? Oh, are you afraid I'm going
to try and get pregnant right now?

524
00:37:28,645 --> 00:37:35,084
Don't worry. Not tonight.

525
00:37:57,507 --> 00:38:00,142
Do you like her?

526
00:38:00,210 --> 00:38:03,245
She is my daughter.

527
00:38:03,313 --> 00:38:05,147
You see, I did it.

528
00:38:05,215 --> 00:38:10,019
I had a child and I raised her
without a husband.

529
00:38:10,086 --> 00:38:15,257
I had this certain plan.
Sasha knew about it.

530
00:38:15,325 --> 00:38:17,793
Doesn't her father know he has a
daughter?

531
00:38:17,861 --> 00:38:18,861
I didn't tell him.

532
00:38:18,929 --> 00:38:19,862
And her?

533
00:38:19,930 --> 00:38:22,031
I didn't tell her either.

534
00:38:22,099 --> 00:38:27,970
Once, when she got especially
persistent, I told her she
couldn't meet him anyway.

535
00:38:28,038 --> 00:38:31,607
She wanted to know why. I said,
"because he is an American".

536
00:38:31,675 --> 00:38:37,613
She got stuck on the idea, she tells
everyone her father is an American,

537
00:38:37,681 --> 00:38:40,616
she speaks to everybody in
English...

538
00:38:40,684 --> 00:38:42,351
So it goes.

539
00:38:42,419 --> 00:38:44,219
Is he actually American?

540
00:38:44,287 --> 00:38:46,288
In a way.

541
00:38:46,356 --> 00:38:48,290
Let me introduce you two.

542
00:38:48,359 --> 00:38:54,797
Sasha, Jill, this is Elena.

543
00:38:54,865 --> 00:38:57,967
Elena, as you know, Sasha is my
old friend.

544
00:38:58,034 --> 00:39:01,203
Mom has told me lots about you.
And not just Mom.

545
00:39:01,271 --> 00:39:03,739
You're sort of a legend around
here.

546
00:39:03,807 --> 00:39:05,875
To my surprise, I am discovering
this for myself.

547
00:39:05,942 --> 00:39:10,913
As well as some other things.

548
00:39:10,981 --> 00:39:13,082
Why did you name her Elena?

549
00:39:13,149 --> 00:39:16,118
Why not?

550
00:39:16,186 --> 00:39:18,754
I see you've met my namesake.

551
00:39:18,822 --> 00:39:22,124
We've become quite good friends
in the past few days.

552
00:39:22,192 --> 00:39:24,927
I don't have any friends!

553
00:39:24,595 --> 00:39:30,833
I'm sorry.
Don't take it personally.

554
00:39:30,901 --> 00:39:34,937
I really don't have any friends.

555
00:39:35,005 --> 00:39:36,639
Why don't you have friends,
Elena?

556
00:39:36,707 --> 00:39:38,540
Do you?

557
00:39:38,509 --> 00:39:40,409
As a matter of fact, yes.

558
00:39:40,477 --> 00:39:42,478
That's just because you're
American.

559
00:39:42,546 --> 00:39:44,580
Around here, we don't do that.

560
00:39:44,648 --> 00:39:46,882
What nonsense you're saying!

561
00:39:46,950 --> 00:39:48,717
Don't you know how many friends
I have?

562
00:39:48,785 --> 00:39:57,159
I know. That's why I said it.

563
00:39:57,227 --> 00:39:59,028
She's so difficult lately.

564
00:39:59,095 --> 00:40:00,696
Adolescence, you know.

565
00:40:00,763 --> 00:40:03,298
Comrades! Comrades! Ladies and
Gentlemen!

566
00:40:03,366 --> 00:40:10,740
Sasha Greenberg is not the only
old friend we are greeting today
after years of separation!

567
00:40:10,807 --> 00:40:16,045
There is another person, well
known to most of you here,

568
00:40:16,113 --> 00:40:18,881
whom we haven't seen in just as
many years as Sasha.

569
00:40:18,949 --> 00:40:25,220
Friends, let us drink to the
ever beautiful Helen of Troy!

570
00:40:25,288 --> 00:40:41,571
#

571
00:41:03,760 --> 00:41:06,529
Excuse me, are you... Helen
Preston?

572
00:41:06,597 --> 00:41:09,665
Yes, yes I am.

573
00:41:09,733 --> 00:41:14,036
You called... Asked me to
come... Here I am.

574
00:41:14,104 --> 00:41:15,872
I am Sasha Greenberg.

575
00:41:15,939 --> 00:41:19,375
Of course! Of course! You're
the famous Greenberg!

576
00:41:19,442 --> 00:41:20,810
Famous? How?

577
00:41:20,878 --> 00:41:22,778
The first physicist refusenik.

578
00:41:22,846 --> 00:41:24,213
The freedom fighter.

579
00:41:24,280 --> 00:41:27,883
So, you came over from America
on an exchange program?

580
00:41:27,751 --> 00:41:31,420
Citizen, you are violating laws
here.

581
00:41:31,488 --> 00:41:33,089
Let's see your pass!

582
00:41:33,156 --> 00:41:38,127
You've been fired from this
institute.

583
00:41:38,195 --> 00:41:41,330
You should've turned in your
pass a long time ago.

584
00:41:41,397 --> 00:41:43,299
I'll be leaving in a few
minutes.

585
00:41:43,366 --> 00:41:44,700
What few minutes?

586
00:41:44,767 --> 00:41:49,305
Chromov, Come on, take his other
arm!

587
00:41:49,372 --> 00:41:50,806
Sasha!

588
00:41:50,874 --> 00:41:52,374
This is a serious offense.

589
00:41:52,442 --> 00:41:56,145
This is a scientific facility, we
have classified information here.

590
00:41:56,213 --> 00:41:59,181
Lucky for us, a comrade called
and informed us.

591
00:41:59,249 --> 00:42:02,618
Otherwise, we'd be taking the
heat for this.

592
00:42:02,685 --> 00:42:06,521
Is that the spy?
Let's have him!

593
00:42:06,589 --> 00:42:10,325
Sasha, I will be behind you.

594
00:42:10,393 --> 00:42:14,196
You're Greenberg?

595
00:42:14,264 --> 00:42:15,064
I am.

596
00:42:15,132 --> 00:42:16,832
You can go.

597
00:42:16,900 --> 00:42:18,801
Why was I detained?

598
00:42:18,869 --> 00:42:21,303
Why don't you ask your buddies
at the institute.

599
00:42:21,371 --> 00:42:24,140
Suddenly, there's this racket -
spy, spy, spy!

600
00:42:24,207 --> 00:42:26,909
The director of the institute
says "he's no spy".

601
00:42:26,977 --> 00:42:30,279
So go on, get out of here before
someone else gives an opinion!

602
00:42:30,346 --> 00:42:31,880
Oh, thank God, it's you!

603
00:42:31,948 --> 00:42:34,850
I called the embassy, I called
Gross.

604
00:42:34,917 --> 00:42:37,486
I guess Gross he must have got
through to them. Thanks.

605
00:42:37,553 --> 00:42:40,589
Did you know this could happen
if you showed up?

606
00:42:40,656 --> 00:42:43,125
I didn't entirely discount the
possibility.

607
00:42:43,193 --> 00:42:45,527
So why did you come?

608
00:42:45,595 --> 00:42:48,430
You asked me to.

609
00:42:48,498 --> 00:42:52,501
Until the end of last century,
Moscow was a completely unique city.

610
00:42:52,568 --> 00:42:57,506
All green and white, yellow and
gold.

611
00:42:57,573 --> 00:43:01,110
Hills were covered with gardens,
white and yellow mansions

612
00:43:01,177 --> 00:43:04,780
and palaces with green roofs
drowning in the gardens,

613
00:43:04,847 --> 00:43:08,850
golden domes crowning churches
and cathedrals..

614
00:43:08,919 --> 00:43:14,423
So, you were saying that your
experiments support my hypothesis?

615
00:43:14,490 --> 00:43:19,128
Now, if gamma is less than one

616
00:43:19,195 --> 00:43:21,897
you must increase the mass by a
factor of two.

617
00:43:21,965 --> 00:43:26,101
Right. But gamma is more than
one in this case.

618
00:43:29,872 --> 00:43:32,441
Can we see your house from here?

619
00:43:32,508 --> 00:43:35,610
My house? Ah, it's over there.

620
00:43:35,678 --> 00:43:38,547
You see the yellow high-rises
right behind there.

621
00:43:41,284 --> 00:43:43,285
Let's go there?

622
00:43:46,456 --> 00:43:50,960
God, I've never felt so happy.

623
00:44:21,191 --> 00:44:23,592
Happy Birthday!
You gonna let me in?

624
00:44:23,660 --> 00:44:27,930
Of course... Come in, I didn't
invite anyone.

625
00:44:27,998 --> 00:44:30,800
Didn't plan anything.
Thanks for remembering.

626
00:44:30,867 --> 00:44:33,202
You're not supposed to invite
anyone.

627
00:44:33,270 --> 00:44:36,972
A birthday party should only be
for those who remember.

628
00:44:37,040 --> 00:44:39,108
You think anyone remembers me
now?

629
00:44:39,176 --> 00:44:41,844
We'll see about that.

630
00:44:41,912 --> 00:44:44,413
(door bell)

631
00:44:44,480 --> 00:44:48,650
You see! And you said no one
would remember!

632
00:44:48,718 --> 00:44:52,421
Oh, Sasha! Happy birthday!

633
00:44:52,488 --> 00:45:01,563
(singing)

634
00:45:01,631 --> 00:45:04,033
Sasha, I want to make a toast!

635
00:45:04,100 --> 00:45:07,369
I'd like to talk to you in
private.

636
00:45:07,437 --> 00:45:11,040
Right now? OK, go ahead.

637
00:45:11,107 --> 00:45:15,845
I want to make a toast!

638
00:45:15,912 --> 00:45:17,980
Where's Natasha?

639
00:45:18,048 --> 00:45:20,049
Where's Helen of Troy?

640
00:45:20,116 --> 00:45:21,683
I'll get them.

641
00:45:21,751 --> 00:45:23,752
I want to tell you I'm in love
with Sasha.

642
00:45:23,819 --> 00:45:28,624
I want everything to be in the
open between us.

643
00:45:28,691 --> 00:45:33,428
Wonderful! Why tell me, of all
people?

644
00:45:33,496 --> 00:45:36,765
Because I thought you were
together.

645
00:45:36,833 --> 00:45:38,901
Sasha and I are old friends.

646
00:45:38,969 --> 00:45:45,241
If you mean sex, then, yes, we
did sleep together... once.

647
00:45:45,308 --> 00:45:47,910
You have my permission.

648
00:45:47,978 --> 00:45:52,147
Even if I were in love with him,
maybe even he with me,

649
00:45:52,215 --> 00:45:54,950
I would still tell you to go
ahead.

650
00:45:55,017 --> 00:45:55,850
Why?

651
00:45:55,918 --> 00:45:58,420
Because Sasha's destiny is not
with me.

652
00:45:58,488 --> 00:46:01,857
There is nothing I can do to
help him, but you can.

653
00:46:01,924 --> 00:46:04,526
What about you?
Don't you wanna leave?

654
00:46:04,594 --> 00:46:11,266
No, It's very hard for a woman to
attain any sort of position in science.

655
00:46:11,334 --> 00:46:19,508
I've achieved a lot here and
Gross appreciates me.

656
00:46:19,575 --> 00:46:23,612
And anyway where would I go?
For what?

657
00:46:23,679 --> 00:46:28,617
Where the hell did everybody go?
I want to make a toast already.

658
00:46:28,684 --> 00:46:44,899
(singing)

659
00:46:57,247 --> 00:46:59,181
Your application is accepted.

660
00:46:59,249 --> 00:47:02,418
The trial period is three
months.

661
00:47:02,485 --> 00:47:05,287
Come back in three months and we
will marry you.

662
00:47:05,355 --> 00:47:07,089
Three months! What do you mean,
in three months?

663
00:47:07,157 --> 00:47:09,959
Her visa expires in two weeks!

664
00:47:10,026 --> 00:47:13,229
Couldn't you speed it up, in
view of the circumstances?

665
00:47:13,296 --> 00:47:18,234
Young man, we do not make
exceptions or "speed things up"!

666
00:47:18,301 --> 00:47:22,137
The law is the same for
everybody!

667
00:47:22,205 --> 00:47:24,773
I know their tricks. You won't
be able to get a visa for longer
than a month

668
00:47:24,840 --> 00:47:26,475
and we'll never be able to get
married.

669
00:47:26,543 --> 00:47:28,910
Fine! I'll contact the Senate.
I'm going to get you out of here!

670
00:47:28,978 --> 00:47:30,712
The American Senate? What does
it have to do with anything?

671
00:47:30,780 --> 00:47:31,913
Everything.

672
00:47:40,890 --> 00:47:44,125
Sasha, this is Rabbi Katz, this
is Sasha.

673
00:47:44,194 --> 00:47:44,926
Shalom.

674
00:47:44,994 --> 00:47:46,695
Shalom.

675
00:47:46,762 --> 00:47:52,234
The rabbi has kindly agreed to
marry us.

676
00:47:52,302 --> 00:47:54,136
But you're not even Jewish!

677
00:47:54,204 --> 00:47:56,505
Now I am. I converted.

678
00:47:56,572 --> 00:48:00,041
Soviet authorities will not
recognize a marriage performed
by an American rabbi.

679
00:48:00,109 --> 00:48:03,845
But the American Senate will, and
I think the American people will.

680
00:48:03,913 --> 00:48:09,884
And then we'll see what your
authorities will have to say.

681
00:48:09,952 --> 00:48:26,101
(MUSIC)

682
00:48:49,359 --> 00:48:54,963
It was my mother's...

683
00:48:55,031 --> 00:48:59,501
Who knows what's hidden inside
this little figurine.

684
00:49:19,389 --> 00:49:21,190
Who is this?

685
00:49:21,257 --> 00:49:25,527
That was my father. He was killed
in 1945. That's his last picture.

686
00:49:25,595 --> 00:49:28,630
Pictures of military uniforms are
forbidden to leave the country.

687
00:49:28,698 --> 00:49:30,432
But it's from World War Two!

688
00:49:30,500 --> 00:49:36,838
I don't make up the laws. You can
leave it behind or I can cut it.

689
00:49:36,906 --> 00:49:40,542
Go ahead. Cut.

690
00:49:51,254 --> 00:49:55,457
Do you think you've outwitted
the experimenters and returned
from unexplored space?

691
00:49:55,525 --> 00:49:58,159
I wasn't thinking that at all,
Master.

692
00:49:58,227 --> 00:50:01,663
On the contrary, you were right
all along:

693
00:50:01,731 --> 00:50:05,000
one does not return from
unexplored space.

694
00:50:05,068 --> 00:50:10,172
I have merely made another pass
into a new unexplored space.

695
00:50:15,612 --> 00:50:17,846
How long's it been since you've
been here?

696
00:50:17,913 --> 00:50:19,181
Seventeen years.

697
00:50:19,249 --> 00:50:21,816
I'll bet you can't wait to see
your friends!

698
00:50:21,884 --> 00:50:23,719
I can't.

699
00:50:23,786 --> 00:50:27,522
They're gonna tell you how great
everything has become, how
things have changed.

700
00:50:27,590 --> 00:50:32,727
Don't believe them. Our lives
are still pretty hard.

701
00:50:39,802 --> 00:50:46,808
You're a guest? Go right ahead,
I'm not even going to open it.

702
00:50:46,876 --> 00:50:50,846
Go on, your friends are waiting.

703
00:50:50,913 --> 00:50:58,019
Your labyrinth has changed so much,
I can't keep a sense of reality.

704
00:50:58,088 --> 00:51:02,657
I have a persistent feeling I'm
in a dream.

705
00:51:02,725 --> 00:51:07,362
Reality can get a little hazy
when one consumes such vast
amounts of alcohol.

706
00:51:07,430 --> 00:51:11,833
That's why I drink, partially,
to regain a sense of reality.

707
00:51:11,901 --> 00:51:13,735
SASHA (VOICE-OVER):
Reality!

708
00:51:13,803 --> 00:51:17,606
Obviously this word still had
some clear meaning for Gross.

709
00:51:17,673 --> 00:51:21,910
As for me, all such words as
reality, logic, sanity,

710
00:51:21,977 --> 00:51:26,448
time, place lost their sense a
long time ago.

711
00:51:26,516 --> 00:51:31,787
It's amazing. Can I really live here?
Can you really be my wife?

712
00:51:31,854 --> 00:51:34,289
I'm really your wife, and I have
some news for you.

713
00:51:34,357 --> 00:51:37,025
We're going to have a baby!

714
00:51:40,330 --> 00:51:43,098
She found him? Thank God.
Where was he?

715
00:51:43,165 --> 00:51:44,766
What happened?

716
00:51:44,834 --> 00:51:47,769
Brenda lost the baby!
She found him.

717
00:51:47,837 --> 00:51:54,876
Yeah. Thank you. Thank you.
I'm coming.

718
00:51:54,944 --> 00:51:58,547
I'm going to have to quit my
job.

719
00:51:58,615 --> 00:52:00,782
If that's what you really want.

720
00:52:00,850 --> 00:52:03,118
I don't think I have a choice.

721
00:52:03,185 --> 00:52:06,622
I, I used to get so angry
whenever people said

722
00:52:06,689 --> 00:52:10,024
women they only go to college to
get husbands,

723
00:52:10,092 --> 00:52:14,996
but, maybe, they were right.

724
00:52:15,064 --> 00:52:20,101
Daddy has to stay home and work
today and tomorrow too...OK?

725
00:52:20,169 --> 00:52:24,072
We'll play later. I have to work
on the phone.

726
00:52:24,139 --> 00:52:25,307
Anything?

727
00:52:25,375 --> 00:52:28,210
No, it's useless. There are no
open positions anywhere.

728
00:52:28,278 --> 00:52:31,246
How about universities? They are
always looking for someone.

729
00:52:31,314 --> 00:52:36,318
Not all universities have the
means and facilities I need to
continue working on my model.

730
00:52:36,386 --> 00:52:39,354
So, now what?

731
00:52:39,422 --> 00:52:43,825
I don't know.
Hughes wants to hire me.

732
00:52:43,893 --> 00:52:47,496
He keeps calling back.
He's got tons of money.

733
00:52:47,564 --> 00:52:51,667
I remember once you preferred
emigration

734
00:52:51,734 --> 00:52:53,968
to working for the military.

735
00:52:54,036 --> 00:52:57,606
Yes, I had somewhere to emigrate
then.

736
00:52:57,673 --> 00:53:06,548
Oh well, if it's a chance for
you to keep working on your
model, how can I say "no"?

737
00:53:06,616 --> 00:53:10,452
By the way, he is paying triple
of what I get now.

738
00:53:37,513 --> 00:53:44,352
I'm, I'm so tired. So much work
in the house.

739
00:53:50,460 --> 00:53:53,728
God, if you only knew how much I
hate you!

740
00:53:53,796 --> 00:53:57,566
I hate your face, I hate your
voice, I hate the air you breathe!

741
00:53:57,633 --> 00:54:01,402
But most of all I hate that
Universe of yours that consumes
absolutely everything.

742
00:54:01,471 --> 00:54:04,873
It sucked away every single drop
of my life! I've had it.

743
00:54:04,941 --> 00:54:07,075
You go sacrifice somebody else's
life for it.

744
00:54:07,142 --> 00:54:08,610
Just go! Worship it.

745
00:54:08,678 --> 00:54:12,681
Go, go! Fuck it for all I care!
Have fun!

746
00:54:12,749 --> 00:54:14,615
I love you. You know that.

747
00:54:14,684 --> 00:54:16,350
Me?! You love me?!

748
00:54:16,418 --> 00:54:20,722
The only thing you worship is
your Universe and your own mind.

749
00:54:20,790 --> 00:54:29,330
(PHONE RINGING)

750
00:54:29,398 --> 00:54:32,433
Yes? Yes, this is... Sasha
Greenberg.

751
00:54:32,502 --> 00:54:37,739
You called before, right?
I remember.

752
00:54:37,807 --> 00:54:40,208
You're making a film about
science.

753
00:54:40,275 --> 00:54:44,813
Your wife?

754
00:54:44,881 --> 00:54:47,181
Umm... maybe not.

755
00:54:47,249 --> 00:54:48,683
What does that mean?

756
00:54:48,751 --> 00:54:50,652
It means that I am not sure.

757
00:54:50,720 --> 00:54:54,756
I am afraid I can't give you
definite answers on everything,
not even science.

758
00:54:54,824 --> 00:54:57,659
So, be forewarned.

759
00:54:57,727 --> 00:55:00,696
Scientific progress is a pretty
ambiguous concept.

760
00:55:00,763 --> 00:55:05,801
After Hiroshima, it is very
fashionable to give up science.

761
00:55:05,868 --> 00:55:08,169
It may have been a sixties'
cliche.

762
00:55:08,338 --> 00:55:10,105
But you didn't give up?

763
00:55:10,172 --> 00:55:15,343
I know that and smoking and
drinking are bad for me, but I
haven't given them up.

764
00:55:15,410 --> 00:55:20,181
Besides, I've already mentioned
an ambiguity, an uncertainty.

765
00:55:20,249 --> 00:55:23,818
Science has done a lot of good
too.

766
00:55:23,886 --> 00:55:26,087
So, if I understand you
correctly,

767
00:55:26,155 --> 00:55:29,290
that a science is much like the
presence of your wife:

768
00:55:29,358 --> 00:55:31,726
a definite "maybe". Agree?

769
00:55:31,794 --> 00:55:39,034
Agree. What're you. Would you
like to have dinner with me?

770
00:55:39,101 --> 00:55:48,677
Maybe... There is a certain ambiguity
involved here, an uncertainty.

771
00:55:48,744 --> 00:55:51,646
And you do not approve?

772
00:55:51,714 --> 00:55:54,649
Strangely enough, I kind of like
it.

773
00:56:01,690 --> 00:56:04,259
The Universe is boundless.

774
00:56:04,326 --> 00:56:10,298
Imagine that on a small planet
orbiting a tertiary star,

775
00:56:10,366 --> 00:56:14,969
one of billions of such stars in
an insignificant galaxy,

776
00:56:15,037 --> 00:56:20,374
a group of microscopic creatures
dares to grasp in their minds

777
00:56:20,442 --> 00:56:24,612
the entire extent of the
Universe!

778
00:56:24,680 --> 00:56:28,983
Let us drink to ourselves,
friends,

779
00:56:29,051 --> 00:56:33,688
the most daring representatives
of the daring race of humankind!

780
00:56:33,755 --> 00:56:38,026
What's there to be proud of?
Man's a dirty animal!

781
00:56:38,093 --> 00:56:41,195
The only species with the bent
and ability to self-destruct,

782
00:56:41,263 --> 00:56:43,665
taking the rest of the planet
with it!

783
00:56:43,733 --> 00:56:48,469
I know, I know. Our atmosphere
is polluted.

784
00:56:48,538 --> 00:56:50,005
Our waters are poisoned.

785
00:56:50,072 --> 00:56:52,941
Entire species of animals are
being annihilated!

786
00:56:53,009 --> 00:56:58,446
We are living on a bomb with the
lit fuse, and still we dare to
be proud of ourselves!

787
00:56:58,514 --> 00:57:04,485
And all human family values and
social traditions have collapsed.

788
00:57:04,554 --> 00:57:09,658
For real, do you have a wife or
not?

789
00:57:09,725 --> 00:57:12,727
In the past two years, she's
left four times and come back
three times.

790
00:57:12,795 --> 00:57:14,529
And why?

791
00:57:14,596 --> 00:57:21,636
Why did she come back? We have
a son together, I asked her to...

792
00:57:21,704 --> 00:57:25,573
and, I guess, she does love me.

793
00:57:25,641 --> 00:57:28,276
Why'd she leave?

794
00:57:28,343 --> 00:57:31,245
She says I ruined her career.

795
00:57:31,313 --> 00:57:38,252
She was a scientist before I...
before she had the baby and quit
work to stay home.

796
00:57:38,320 --> 00:57:40,956
You're a male chauvinist?!

797
00:57:41,023 --> 00:57:43,758
Bullshit! I hate those labels!

798
00:57:43,826 --> 00:57:46,962
For the past two years she's
been working anyway.

799
00:57:47,029 --> 00:57:49,698
And before that she's always
done what she's wanted.

800
00:57:49,765 --> 00:57:53,835
I've yet to see a married woman
who does whatever she wants!

801
00:57:53,903 --> 00:57:56,871
You two should get along
splendidly.

802
00:57:56,939 --> 00:57:59,674
My God! You're so beautiful!

803
00:58:04,213 --> 00:58:07,949
Are you Helen?
Nice to meet you. I'm Jill.

804
00:58:08,017 --> 00:58:13,888
In eighteen years, he's never once
said thank you for anything I've done!

805
00:58:13,956 --> 00:58:16,724
What're you talking about?

806
00:58:16,792 --> 00:58:20,528
Did you thank me every time I
came home with a paycheck?
It's ridiculous.

807
00:58:20,595 --> 00:58:24,465
No, it's not. You earned your
paycheck doing what you loved best!

808
00:58:24,533 --> 00:58:26,201
What did I get for my work?!

809
00:58:26,268 --> 00:58:28,870
You've done what women have done
for centuries.

810
00:58:28,938 --> 00:58:32,173
You're such a Male chauvinist!

811
00:58:32,241 --> 00:58:34,275
I never asked for your
sacrifices.

812
00:58:34,343 --> 00:58:36,745
You wanted me to give up my
career!

813
00:58:36,812 --> 00:58:41,716
To compromise all my principles
and live on blood money you got
for making bombs!

814
00:58:41,784 --> 00:58:45,987
Nobody, absolutely nobody forced
you into any of it!

815
00:58:46,055 --> 00:58:50,391
Besides, if you want to talk
about sacrifices, you should
try eating one of your dinners!

816
00:58:50,459 --> 00:58:52,894
I'm an astrophysicist Sasha.
I'm not your cook!

817
00:58:52,962 --> 00:58:57,832
So be an astrophysicist!
Nobody's stopping you.

818
00:58:57,900 --> 00:59:03,371
Professor, you know how much
respect I have for you,

819
00:59:03,438 --> 00:59:07,575
but there is something I wish to
steal.

820
00:59:07,642 --> 00:59:09,144
It is Sasha?

821
00:59:09,211 --> 00:59:12,914
The very one.
Will you permit me?

822
00:59:12,982 --> 00:59:15,150
What can I do?
I can refuse you nothing.

823
00:59:15,217 --> 00:59:18,052
Thank you, professor.

824
00:59:18,120 --> 00:59:25,860
It's so stuffy in here. Let's go
outside for a few minutes.

825
00:59:25,928 --> 00:59:27,929
Come on, let's go.

826
00:59:27,997 --> 00:59:29,830
We'll be back in a minute.

827
00:59:29,899 --> 00:59:31,599
It's right around here.

828
00:59:31,666 --> 00:59:36,938
SASHA (VOICE-OVER):
Moscow. The familiar city of my youth,

829
00:59:37,006 --> 00:59:39,874
and at the same time completely
different.

830
00:59:39,942 --> 00:59:42,310
We've been driving for half an
hour.

831
00:59:42,378 --> 00:59:45,680
A whole half hour without
alcohol.

832
00:59:45,748 --> 00:59:48,682
It might actually be good for
your health.

833
00:59:48,750 --> 00:59:52,487
SASHA (VOICE-OVER):
I hoped to find here the answers
to the questions

834
00:59:52,554 --> 00:59:57,725
I am struggling with, instead
I've got more questions.

835
00:59:57,792 --> 01:00:01,629
Will I manage to find answers to
them?

836
01:00:01,696 --> 01:00:07,201
And this is where we live these
days.

837
01:00:07,269 --> 01:00:13,007
When my daughter was born, I
applied for a new place.

838
01:00:13,075 --> 01:00:18,146
It took three years. You remember
my old communal apartment -

839
01:00:18,213 --> 01:00:22,650
what a rough time I had with
Elena there.

840
01:00:22,717 --> 01:00:27,688
Now we have two rooms. It's
pretty far, but it's alright.
The Metro is fast.

841
01:00:27,756 --> 01:00:29,990
Is Elena coming right back?

842
01:00:30,059 --> 01:00:33,428
Uh uh. She is spending the
night at her grandparents'.

843
01:00:33,495 --> 01:00:37,398
There's your vodka.

844
01:00:37,466 --> 01:00:39,700
Is she my daughter?

845
01:00:39,768 --> 01:00:43,504
What difference does it make?

846
01:00:43,572 --> 01:00:47,041
What do you mean, what
difference? I want to know.

847
01:00:47,109 --> 01:00:55,349
Don't bother asking, I'm not
going to tell you anyway.

848
01:00:55,818 --> 01:01:02,056
Let's drink to the mysteries in
life, um?

849
01:01:17,072 --> 01:01:19,174
Natasha, wait...

850
01:01:19,241 --> 01:01:24,813
Don't say a word, Sasha. I am
not blind, I have seen your
harem of women.

851
01:01:42,131 --> 01:01:44,365
Look at me. Look at me.

852
01:01:44,433 --> 01:01:48,169
My body is just as good as
twenty years ago.

853
01:01:48,237 --> 01:01:50,704
Aren't you happy I brought you
here?

854
01:01:50,772 --> 01:01:54,909
Tomorrow we'll dance the tango
at my parents'.

855
01:01:54,976 --> 01:02:00,814
You won't believe this. All the
old records are still there.

856
01:02:00,882 --> 01:02:03,884
Nothing has changed at their
house.

857
01:02:03,952 --> 01:02:06,620
Do you remember the old church
next door?

858
01:02:06,688 --> 01:02:11,859
The one that used to be all
nailed up?

859
01:02:11,927 --> 01:02:14,062
We used to sneak in at night?

860
01:02:14,129 --> 01:02:21,169
It's being restored.
It looks like new.

861
01:02:21,236 --> 01:02:25,073
We'll go there,
I'll show you around.

862
01:02:25,141 --> 01:02:29,177
Mom! It's me.

863
01:02:29,245 --> 01:02:35,850
SASHA (VOICE-OVER):
This girl. She did not even
exist when I left.

864
01:02:35,917 --> 01:02:38,419
Everyone hardly changed at all,
but out of nowhere,

865
01:02:38,487 --> 01:02:41,355
as if out of sea foam - there
she was.

866
01:02:41,423 --> 01:02:44,892
There was something mystical
about that.

867
01:02:44,960 --> 01:02:46,760
Don't come in here.
I am not alone.

868
01:02:46,828 --> 01:02:50,098
I know you're not.

869
01:02:50,165 --> 01:02:52,100
Why did you come back then?

870
01:02:52,167 --> 01:02:55,036
It's my house too.

871
01:02:55,104 --> 01:02:57,772
It is. Now go to sleep, darling.

872
01:02:57,839 --> 01:03:01,876
SASHA (VOICE-OVER):
All my days in Moscow I couldn't
stop thinking about Elena

873
01:03:01,943 --> 01:03:04,278
and, look, here she was.

874
01:03:04,346 --> 01:03:08,016
Now she will move furniture all
night long.

875
01:03:08,083 --> 01:03:11,719
SASHA (VOICE-OVER):
The presence of this girl

876
01:03:11,786 --> 01:03:14,955
was definitely changing my
perception of the world.

877
01:03:15,024 --> 01:03:17,625
Do you know how it is in science
fiction,

878
01:03:17,692 --> 01:03:20,395
when you return from a trip to
the past

879
01:03:20,462 --> 01:03:23,197
to find out you accidentally
changed something?

880
01:03:23,265 --> 01:03:26,300
Both your past and your present
are no longer yours.

881
01:03:26,368 --> 01:03:28,869
They may seem the same at first
glance,

882
01:03:28,937 --> 01:03:32,340
but you look closer and no -
there is this girl.

883
01:03:32,408 --> 01:03:39,080
So, you inevitably start
re-examining everything else,
including yourself.

884
01:03:39,148 --> 01:03:46,554
We cannot be the same, life
cannot go on as before.

885
01:03:52,761 --> 01:03:54,995
Good morning.

886
01:03:55,064 --> 01:03:59,800
Good morning. Although I am not
sure it is morning yet.

887
01:03:59,868 --> 01:04:02,903
I've wanted to talk to you.
Let's walk.

888
01:04:02,971 --> 01:04:08,776
Sure, let's. After all, what
else is there to do around here
at this time?

889
01:04:08,844 --> 01:04:16,184
Oh, sure. In America, you can
probably go to a cafe at three
in the morning,

890
01:04:16,251 --> 01:04:18,319
at 5 in the morning, at 7
o'clock.

891
01:04:18,387 --> 01:04:19,620
Yes.

892
01:04:19,688 --> 01:04:24,392
I hate it! I hate all of this.

893
01:04:24,460 --> 01:04:26,427
Because there aren't any cafes?

894
01:04:26,495 --> 01:04:33,234
Because there isn't any life.
Don't make jokes, sir.

895
01:04:33,302 --> 01:04:37,005
Do you think you're my father?

896
01:04:37,072 --> 01:04:44,012
I don't really know.
What do you think?

897
01:04:44,079 --> 01:04:48,716
I don't know. But I don't think
so.

898
01:04:48,783 --> 01:04:51,252
According to my papers, I am
sixteen.

899
01:04:51,320 --> 01:04:56,457
Which means that you left at least
six months before she got pregnant.

900
01:04:56,525 --> 01:04:58,893
Of course, she could've forged
them.

901
01:04:58,960 --> 01:05:00,495
Who?

902
01:05:00,562 --> 01:05:04,232
My mother. She can do anything.

903
01:05:04,299 --> 01:05:07,402
You're so harsh.

904
01:05:07,569 --> 01:05:13,975
I hate her.
She is an old lying bitch.

905
01:05:14,043 --> 01:05:18,546
Well, obviously our perspectives
are a little different.

906
01:05:18,613 --> 01:05:21,515
Want to know what I think of
your mother?

907
01:05:21,583 --> 01:05:25,486
Yeah.

908
01:05:25,554 --> 01:05:28,189
She's a lovely, talented woman.

909
01:05:28,257 --> 01:05:33,094
A hard worker. Alone, she
managed not only to have a
career in science,

910
01:05:33,162 --> 01:05:37,098
but to raise you as well.
That's a miracle in itself.

911
01:05:37,166 --> 01:05:41,302
Through all this she's retained
a youthful sense of romanticism.

912
01:05:41,370 --> 01:05:46,374
You call her a liar, but I'd
rather think of her as romantic.

913
01:05:46,442 --> 01:05:49,910
Because she lies? Yeah?

914
01:05:49,979 --> 01:05:53,914
We were talking about tomorrow.
You know what she wants to do?

915
01:05:53,983 --> 01:05:56,884
She was dreaming of showing me
an old church.

916
01:05:56,952 --> 01:06:01,589
I'm sure. She takes all her men
to that stupid church.

917
01:06:01,656 --> 01:06:03,891
She's been there a thousand
times.

918
01:06:03,959 --> 01:06:05,526
You are cruel.

919
01:06:05,594 --> 01:06:08,062
You're cruel! Don't you see?

920
01:06:08,130 --> 01:06:13,734
If you loved her even a little
bit, you wouldn't make her sound
like such a saint.

921
01:06:13,802 --> 01:06:15,436
I don't think I understand.

922
01:06:15,504 --> 01:06:18,272
And what do you do understand?

923
01:06:18,340 --> 01:06:24,378
I want to tell you about myself.

924
01:06:24,446 --> 01:06:29,717
I grew up under the portrait of
a man I never met.

925
01:06:29,785 --> 01:06:32,553
He was a hero, they said.

926
01:06:32,621 --> 01:06:37,925
A man who wasn't afraid to apply
for emigration when his chances
were nil.

927
01:06:37,992 --> 01:06:42,096
But mostly, he was going to
conquer the Universe.

928
01:06:42,163 --> 01:06:46,934
A genius. The new Einstein.

929
01:06:47,001 --> 01:06:53,441
Kiss me.

930
01:06:53,508 --> 01:07:02,550
Not like that. For real.

931
